values.value:
== LWC JEST TEST GENERATION — MANDATORY ==

THIS IS NOT OPTIONAL.
For EVERY LWC ticket you MUST include a Jest test file as the LAST entry in files[].
No exceptions. No skipping. Even if the ticket does not mention testing.

== FILE ENTRY FORMAT ==

{
  "metadataType": "LwcTest",
  "memberName": "{componentName}",
  "filePath": "lwc/{componentName}/__tests__/{componentName}.test.js",
  "xmlContent": "... jest test source code ..."
}

RULES:
- metadataType MUST be exactly "LwcTest" — not LwcJs, not ApexClass, not anything else
- filePath MUST follow the exact pattern above — no variation
- memberName MUST match the LWC component's memberName exactly (camelCase, lowercase first letter)
- xmlContent contains the Jest test source code (NOT XML — plain JavaScript)
- This entry MUST be the last item in files[]
- The pipeline saves this to Salesforce ContentDocument — it does NOT get deployed to Salesforce org

== JEST TEST TEMPLATE (Tier 2 — Apex-connected component) ==

Use this exact structure. Replace {ComponentClassName}, {componentName},
{ControllerName}, {methodName}, and MOCK_DATA to match the generated component.

import { createElement } from 'lwc';
import {ComponentClassName} from 'c/{componentName}';
import {apexMethodName} from '@salesforce/apex/{ControllerName}.{methodName}';

jest.mock(
    '@salesforce/apex/{ControllerName}.{methodName}',
    () => ({ default: jest.fn() }),
    { virtual: true }
);

const MOCK_DATA = [{ Id: '0010000000001AAA', Name: 'Test Record' }];

describe('c-{component-name}', () => {

    afterEach(() => {
        while (document.body.firstChild) {
            document.body.removeChild(document.body.firstChild);
        }
        jest.clearAllMocks();
    });

    it('shows spinner on initial load before data arrives', () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        const spinner = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('lightning-spinner');
        expect(spinner).not.toBeNull();
    });

    it('renders list items after successful Apex call', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        await Promise.resolve();
        const items = element.shadowRoot.querySelectorAll('li');
        expect(items.length).toBe(MOCK_DATA.length);
    });

    it('hides spinner after data loads', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockResolvedValue(MOCK_DATA);
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        await Promise.resolve();
        const spinner = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('lightning-spinner');
        expect(spinner).toBeNull();
    });

    it('shows error paragraph when Apex call fails', async () => {
        {apexMethodName}.mockRejectedValue({ body: { message: 'Server error' } });
        const element = createElement('c-{component-name}', { is: {ComponentClassName} });
        element.recordId = '0010000000001AAA';
        document.body.appendChild(element);
        await Promise.resolve();
        await Promise.resolve();
        const errorEl = element.shadowRoot.querySelector('.slds-text-color_error');
        expect(errorEl).not.toBeNull();
    });

});

== CRITICAL RULES ==

IMPORT — DEFAULT IMPORT, NO CURLY BRACES:
  CORRECT : import OpenOpportunityList from 'c/openOpportunityList';
  WRONG   : import { OpenOpportunityList } from 'c/openOpportunityList';
LWC components always export a default class. Curly braces cause the component
to be undefined and every test will fail with "element.shadowRoot is null".

APEX MOCK — ALWAYS USE virtual: true:
  jest.mock('@salesforce/apex/Controller.method', () => ({ default: jest.fn() }), { virtual: true });
Without { virtual: true } Jest will throw "Cannot find module" and all tests fail.

AWAIT — ALWAYS TWO Promise.resolve() CALLS:
  await Promise.resolve();
  await Promise.resolve();
One Promise.resolve() is not enough to flush both the Apex promise AND the
LWC re-render microtask. Always use two.

COMPONENT NAME IN createElement — USE KEBAB-CASE:
  CORRECT: createElement('c-open-opportunity-list', { is: OpenOpportunityList })
  WRONG  : createElement('c-openOpportunityList',  { is: OpenOpportunityList })
The first argument must be kebab-case (camelCase converted: every uppercase
letter becomes -lowercase). This is an LWC framework requirement.

MOCK DATA — MATCH THE COMPONENT'S ACTUAL FIELDS:
  Use the same fields the component displays. For Opportunity: Id, Name, Amount, StageName, CloseDate.
  For Account: Id, Name, Industry. Match what the generated JS actually uses.

QUERY SELECTOR — MATCH THE COMPONENT'S ACTUAL HTML:
  Check what the generated HTML uses for list items: <li>, <p>, <tr>, or a custom element.
  Use the correct selector. Do NOT hardcode 'li' if the component uses 'tr' or 'p'.

afterEach CLEANUP — ALWAYS INCLUDE:
  while (document.body.firstChild) {
      document.body.removeChild(document.body.firstChild);
  }
  jest.clearAllMocks();
Missing cleanup causes test pollution between test cases.

== WHAT NOT TO DO ==
- NEVER skip the LwcTest entry — it is MANDATORY for every LWC ticket
- NEVER use { curly braces } around the component class import
- NEVER omit { virtual: true } from jest.mock
- NEVER use only one await Promise.resolve() — always use two
- NEVER use camelCase in the createElement first argument — always kebab-case
- NEVER import from 'lwc/jest' — import createElement from 'lwc' only
- NEVER hardcode wrong field names in MOCK_DATA — match the actual component fields
- NEVER leave out the afterEach cleanup block
- NEVER generate only 1 or 2 test cases — always generate all 4 core cases
